{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:27:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:27:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14693"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14693"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.61,0.1,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7386"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43513"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3649"},{"type":"tags","id":"6609"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18023"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of a painless skin lesion on his right forearm. He works as a wool processor in a textile factory. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is a 3 cm black eschar with significant surrounding non-pitting oedema on his right forearm. There is no lymphadenopathy or systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely implicated pathogen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bartonella henselae","Bacillus anthracis","Clostridium perfringens","Streptococcus pyogenes","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests cutaneous anthrax infection caused by \u003Cstrong\u003EBacillus anthracis\u003C/strong\u003E. The characteristic features include a painless black eschar with surrounding non-pitting oedema, and crucially, the occupational exposure to animal products (wool processing). \u003Cem\u003EB. anthracis\u003C/em\u003E forms spores that can remain dormant in animal products for many years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/strong\u003E is the causative organism of cat scratch disease, which typically presents with regional lymphadenopathy following a cat scratch or bite. While it can cause skin lesions, these are usually papules or pustules at the inoculation site rather than an eschar.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClostridium perfringens\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with gas gangrene, which presents with severe pain, crepitus, and rapidly spreading tissue destruction, none of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes erythematous, painful cellulitis or erysipelas with well-demarcated borders. It does not cause eschar formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E can cause skin infections, particularly in burn wounds or immunocompromised patients. While it can cause ecthyma gangrenosum (a black eschar with surrounding erythema), this typically occurs in immunocompromised patients with sepsis. This patient is immunocompetent, well, and has the crucial occupational exposure history pointing to anthrax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of anthrax requires a high index of suspicion based on occupational exposure history. While cutaneous anthrax accounts for 95% of cases and usually remains localised, early recognition and treatment are essential to prevent progression to systemic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cutaneous anthrax typically presents as a painless black eschar with surrounding oedema.","A history of exposure to animal products, particularly hides or wool, is crucial in diagnosing anthrax.","Bacillus anthracis spores can remain dormant in animal products for many years before causing infection."],"references":["Rathnayake D, Sinclair R. Tropical and exotic dermatoses and ulcers. Aust Fam Physician. 2014;43(9):604-609."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43513"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14693"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43513"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T20:39:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T20:41:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7386"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58054"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attri